My favorite similar story was about some singer or actor I think having a meeting w/ industry people and three pale men in suits came in the room, similar to descriptions of "men in black", and when they introduced themselves they said they were "from the South", which means Hell

These entities are supposedly recent cadavers animated by demons similarly to vampires in Eastern European folklore. The meeting would then involve the man selling his soul to them in exchange of getting to have a world-renowned career in music or cinema.

What makes it interesting to me is Fr. Seraphim Rose also mentions a dying man saying he is going on a ship to Sicily before being dragged down to Hell, Sicily being a hot and volcanic place. In the US the South is also hot, deserted, etc. so the same symbolism is possible.

Anti-German sentiment in video games has always been purely apolitical inertia, when people are allowed to make mods on their own, getting to play as a Nazi is always one of the first things everyone wants to do. Just a fact of life. And of Eastern European beach shop coffee mugs

There actually used to be old German uncle conspiracy theories that all American video games being about "fighting Nazis" is a way to brainwash US boys into hating German people to make a future WW3 draft easier, but the truth is simply no one cares about politics in FPS games.
